@jsrailton @RandoriSecurity @campuscodi It is indeed a balancing act, especially given the opaque nature of the landscape. 

We do not give specifics about zero-days. We want them to focus on the rest of the kill chain. We'll work with them to ensure they maintain resiliency in the face of such a compromise.

@jsrailton @RandoriSecurity @campuscodi Good questions, and we have internal procedures that govern our disclosure policy that balances the risks associated (of which we are certainly aware). We are working towards and intend to publish this policy for transparency.

@CharlesDardaman @hacks4pancakes @WeldPond Good question--we did not recommend any mitigations that are specific to the vulnerability. The experience resulted in customers designing in-depth defenses, including introspection, alerting, segmentation, etc. that were proven quite effective.
@SeanHarcourt @MalwareJake Your point is taken. We are acutely aware of the risks and actively balance the risks associated. We do no believe ourselves invulnerable.

@hacks4pancakes @WeldPond Firstly, thank you for the discussion. We aren't expecting everyone to align on such a complex and frankly opaque topic. Our customers were not left vulnerable--in fact they were arguably more secure & able to catch us without knowledge of the vuln (which is the goal).

@jsrailton @RandoriSecurity @campuscodi We welcome the discussion! This conversation has to happen--defending against individual vulns has proven ineffective. Focusing on the vuln-du-jour and not broad protections and processes is missing the point. Becoming resilient in the face of unknown threats is the goal.

@hacks4pancakes @WeldPond "Pwning is simply not the point of a pen test. Education and improving security are." 

100% agreed. Moving away from being reactive to each and every 0day and being able to detect attacks regardless of the vulnerability is the "education and improving security" you refer to.
@hacks4pancakes @WeldPond In our experience we have seen vast improvements in resiliency when the perspective shifts from "how do I patch this" to "how could I detect the next one?".

@jfslowik Customers would not be able to grant us the access we achieved. That is part of the point of using real capabilities--customers are made aware of their blind spots such as lack of visibility into these opaque systems. This is where BAS and simulation products fall flat.

@dangoodin001 @porkbellyfuture @daveaitel We help customers implement categorical defenses and assess their ability to detect attempted exploitation and compromise. They implement new techniques and procedures to encompass entire classes of threats. They reset the board and we try again until they catch us.

@dangoodin001 @porkbellyfuture @daveaitel We‚Äôve seen change happen: default-deny, segmentation & monitoring prove remarkably effective. Using a small number of bugs to build, test, and validate defenses against a large number of unknowns is the goal.

@SeanHarcourt @MalwareJake Customers would not be able to grant us the access we achieved. That is part of the point of using real capabilities--customers are made aware of their blind spots such as lack of visibility into these opaque systems. This is where BAS and simulation products fall flat.

@hacks4pancakes @campuscodi The point is resilience. The lessons learned stem from the opportunity to practice w/ an authentic adversary. From recon to compromise to recon again to on-system actions & beyond. We see implementation of broad defenses & techniques to encompass entire classes of threats.

@evacide @pwnpnw We‚Äôre all on the same side here #teamdefense. Our goal is resilience. There will always be 0day--the discussion has to move to categorical defense. Research shows the average 0day lives for 6+ years. We want better detection & response to this class of threat for the greater good

@brianjmoran @MalwareJake Part of the process (and the discussion we're driving toward) is helping implement categorical defenses that thwart attempts--even in the face of unknown threats. They reset the board, we subsequently test until they are able to catch us without worrying about the zero-day.

@evacide @pwnpnw The greater good is served by making the industry more resilient. Find and fix isn‚Äôt sufficient. There will always be unknowns and we have to defend against them. An effective strategy is to build and validate categorical defenses that withstand entire classes of threats.
@pwnpnw @evacide For a bit of background on our philosophy regarding the use of zero-days: https://t.co/nMvtS4GOZr

@philipwhiuk @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack They implement categorical defenses and assess their ability to detect attempted exploitation and compromise. They implement new techniques and procedures to encompass entire classes of threats. They reset the board and we try again until they catch us.
@philipwhiuk @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack The next time a zero-day comes out in a similar target, they feel prepared.
@303sec If you'd like to read some background on the philosophy behind our use of zero-days, I'd recommend starting here: https://t.co/nMvtS4GOZr

@_darrenmartyn @jayjacobs @ftp_alun @paragonsec @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @RandoriAttack What @_darrenmartyn said ^. Customers would not be able to grant us the access we achieved. That is part of the point of using real capabilities--customers are made aware of their blind spots such as lack of visibility into these opaque systems.

@ftp_alun @paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack It isn't just the internal intrusion validation that the use of zero-days affords. In that scope I agree you could validate it other ways. The value comes from the holistic experience, from reconnaissance to attempt to compromise to recon again to on-system actions, and beyond.

@ftp_alun @paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Also, in this particular scenario (PAN firewall), I don't think a customer could grant us access to such a device the way that we authentically did so--the system is locked down from the customer perspective.

@ftp_alun @paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Does that assume zero-days are the exclusive means of intrusion? That isn't how we operate--they're just a component used when necessary. We attempt to mimic what nation state threat actors are doing and to strive for authentic access in doing so. N-Day/0-day/phishing/...

@ftp_alun @paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack I take your point that assisted access can open up new means of testing and validation--totally agree! Occasionally we do engage our customers in that fashion.

@ftp_alun @paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack I would argue that falls under the category of defending known threats (here is the entry path we predict) rather than confronting the harder challenge of implementing defenses broadly across your attack surface to withstand unknown attacks.

@lsaiz @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Zero-day exist right now--loads of them. Zero-day will exist tomorrow, and the next day. We need to move the conversation away from a reactionary response to each new one and focus on categorical improvements that can detect them generically.

@paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Absolutely agree with you on that being a large number of breaches. We have experience dealing with some that fall out of that particular description, and our customers are often looking ahead to what tomorrow's threat may look like.

@jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack That is a great point &I have some experience in that area. I ran @thezdi and the first Pwn2Own contests--at both we had instances of co-discoveries. But reliable numbers are hard to come by. I will say that if we have indication of such, it would trigger a disclosure process.

@paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Firstly, we take your point on co-discovery--that is a risk that we are aware of and actively track to the best of our ability. It is worth noting that no active exploitation occurred in the window under scrutiny.

@paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack As for TTPs/BAS/etc., we do not believe those to be adequate simulacrums of advanced attackers. Everything we do is unassisted by the customer to remain as authentic as possible.

@paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Let me answer with a question: Under what circumstances does an organization get to test all the policies and procedures they put in place to detect adversaries *after* initial compromise?

@paragonsec @jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack How can they be sure those would work? If we utilize a 0day our customers must learn to deal with the reality that they cannot patch. Then, they realize they can implement multiple layers of visibility and introspection to detect *any* 0day. If they patch, they defend against one

@jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Yes, exactly. We are acutely aware of the risks associated with maintaining these capabilities. We actively weigh the risks and attempt our best at balancing them.

@CharlesDardaman @RandoriAttack That is an astute observation and we are acutely aware of those risks. They have informed our procedures around these decisions and we actively attempt to balance them.

@jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack Might I suggest taking a look at this post that is mentioned in the advisory as to why we operate with zero-days: https://t.co/nMvtS4GOZr

@jayjacobs @dcuthbert @lorenzofb @_darrenmartyn @RandoriAttack To elaborate a bit more and answer your question about testing response: yes precisely--the ability to validate designed procedures that have never been activated is a fundamental benefit to testing with authentic zero-day.
